<ArticleLayout
  title="Bedroom Drawers, Tallboys and Dressers: What to Check Before You Buy"
  description="A practical Australian guide to choosing bedroom drawers, tallboys and dressers, including size, drawer depth, room clearance, shared bedrooms, renters and small rooms."
  category="Bedroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bedroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A calm bedroom with a timber dresser, folded clothes and warm natural light"
>
  <p>
    Bedroom drawers, tallboys and dressers are often bought when clothing starts to spill
    out of the wardrobe, clean laundry stays in baskets or the top of the bedside table has
    become a second cupboard. Extra furniture can help, but it does not automatically fix the
    problem.
  </p>
  <p>
    A drawer unit that is too wide, too deep, too tall or awkward to open can make the room
    harder to use. It may block a walkway, crowd a robe track, collect piles on top or hide
    items that should have been sorted first. The better starting point is to work out what
    needs to fold, what should hang, what can move elsewhere and how much clearance the room
    actually has.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide covers what to check before choosing a tallboy, dresser, chest of drawers or
    similar bedroom furniture. For broader room planning, start with the{" "}
    <a href="/categories/bedroom/">Bedroom</a> category and the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-storage-ideas-small-australian-rooms/">small bedroom storage guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Take</h2>
  <p>
    A useful bedroom drawer unit should make everyday clothing easier to manage without
    overwhelming the room. For many Australian bedrooms, the right choice is not the biggest
    tallboy or the widest dresser. It is the piece that fits the available wall, opens
    properly, holds the items that genuinely need drawers and leaves the room easy to move
    through.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the unit becomes another surface for clutter, blocks wardrobe access or creates
    heavier drawers than the household can manage, it may not be solving the real issue.
    Sorting first is less exciting than buying furniture, but it usually leads to a better
    choice.
  </p>

  <h2>Start With What Needs to Go in Drawers</h2>
  <p>
    Before measuring furniture, list what actually needs to live in drawers. Common drawer
    items include underwear, socks, sleepwear, activewear, T-shirts, kids' clothing, folded
    workwear, school uniforms and smaller accessories. These items are easier to manage when
    they have clear categories rather than being stacked in one mixed pile.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some things may not belong in bedroom drawers at all. Paperwork, old electronics, random
    cables, spare towels, unused linen, shopping bags and rarely used clutter can quickly
    turn a drawer unit into a hiding place. If the bedroom is already crowded, buying more
    drawers for unsorted items can simply move the mess into a different box.
  </p>
  <p>
    Decide what should hang, what can fold, what belongs under the bed, what should move to a
    linen cupboard and what can leave the home. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-wardrobe-organisation-what-to-sort-before-buying-storage/">wardrobe organisation guide</a>{" "}
    can help with hanging versus folding decisions, while the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/under-bed-storage-what-to-measure-before-you-buy/">under-bed storage guide</a>{" "}
    is useful for seasonal clothes and occasional items.
  </p>

  <h2>Tallboy, Low Dresser or Chest of Drawers?</h2>
  <p>
    A tallboy uses vertical space and can suit rooms where floor area is limited. It may work
    well beside a wardrobe, in a narrow wall gap or in a room where a wide dresser would
    crowd the bed. The trade-off is height. A tall unit can feel visually heavy, and upper
    drawers may be less convenient for daily items.
  </p>
  <p>
    A low dresser usually needs more wall width, but it can provide a wider top surface and
    easier access to the top drawers. That surface can be useful for a lamp, jewellery tray
    or folded laundry waiting to be put away, but it can also become a permanent clutter
    zone. A chest of drawers sits somewhere in the middle, depending on height, width and
    drawer layout.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wider units can hold folded clothing well, but they need enough room for drawers to open.
    Narrow units can fit tighter spaces, but bulky jumpers, uniforms or linen may not sit
    neatly inside them. A dresser with a mirror may suit some rooms, while a simple drawer
    unit may be more flexible if the layout changes.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the Room Before Choosing Furniture</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the wall width first, then measure the depth available from the wall into the
    room. After that, measure drawer-opening clearance. A unit can fit against the wall and
    still be frustrating if the drawers hit the bed, a wardrobe door, a rug edge or the side
    of a doorway.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check walkways beside the bed, robe tracks, sliding wardrobe doors, bedroom doors,
    ensuite doors and balcony doors. Also check power points, vents, windows, curtain drops
    and skirting boards. Older homes, apartments and rentals can have awkward wall sections
    that look usable until furniture arrives.
  </p>
  <p>
    Flooring matters too. Carpet, rugs, tiled floors and timber-look flooring can change how
    a unit sits and how easily drawers open. Product photos often show larger bedrooms than
    many Australian homes have, so measure the real room rather than relying on the display
    setting.
  </p>

  <h2>Drawer Size, Depth, Runners and Everyday Access</h2>
  <p>
    Deep drawers can be useful for bulky items such as jumpers, tracksuits, school uniforms
    and spare folded pieces, but they can hide socks, small accessories and lighter clothing.
    Shallow drawers are easier for small items, but they may not suit thicker clothing or
    rolled linen.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wide drawers hold more, but they can become heavier when full. Drawer runners affect how
    smoothly the drawer opens and whether the drawer feels suitable for daily use. Handles
    also matter in narrow rooms because protruding handles can catch clothing or reduce
    walkway clearance.
  </p>
  <p>
    Soft-close runners can be convenient, but they are not essential for every household.
    More important is whether the drawers open fully without hitting the bed, robe or door.
    Check manufacturer weight limits, avoid overloading drawers or runners, and use drawer
    dividers only after deciding what each drawer is meant to hold.
  </p>

  <h2>Wardrobe Overflow, Folded Clothes and Linen</h2>
  <p>
    A drawer unit can support a wardrobe, but it should not become an overflow dump. Folded
    clothes need categories: workwear, activewear, sleepwear, T-shirts, kids' clothes, spare
    uniforms or seasonal pieces. If every drawer becomes mixed, the furniture will be harder
    to maintain.
  </p>
  <p>
    Spare linen may not belong in bedroom drawers unless it is used in that room and can be
    kept in a clear set. Guest sheets, spare doonas and seasonal blankets may work better in
    a linen cupboard, under-bed container or another labelled zone. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedding-and-linen-basics-for-australian-bedrooms/">bedding and linen basics guide</a>{" "}
    covers sheet sets, spare linen and seasonal bedding in more detail.
  </p>
  <p>
    Workwear, uniforms and activewear often need fast access, especially in shared homes or
    family bedrooms. Seasonal clothing may not deserve prime drawer space all year. If the
    wardrobe is crowded, improve the wardrobe plan first, then buy drawers only for the
    items that genuinely need them.
  </p>

  <h2>Surface Space, Clutter and Bedroom Flow</h2>
  <p>
    Low dressers create useful surface space, but that surface can attract clutter quickly.
    Jewellery trays, folded laundry, a lamp or a small decor item can work if they have a
    clear purpose. Receipts, skincare, devices, spare clothes and half-sorted laundry can
    turn the top into another unfinished task.
  </p>
  <p>
    Tallboys reduce surface area, which can help if clutter is a problem, but they may feel
    heavier in a small room. A unit that blocks bed-making, vacuuming, wardrobe access or the
    normal path through the room may be more annoying than helpful.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the dresser top is mostly holding night-time items, the bedside area may need a
    better plan. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedside-table-setup-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">bedside table setup guide</a>{" "}
    covers height, drawer access, lamps and charging in more detail.
  </p>

  <h2>Small Bedrooms, Rentals and Shared Rooms</h2>
  <p>
    Small bedrooms may suit a tall narrow unit rather than a wide dresser, but only if the
    height, drawer access and placement make sense. A narrow wall beside a robe can look
    tempting, but check whether drawers can open without blocking the walkway or robe track.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters may prefer freestanding furniture that can move later, but manufacturer guidance
    still matters. Avoid drilling, permanent fixing or wall changes unless approved. If wall
    fixing or installation is required, use appropriate qualified help where needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Shared bedrooms need clearer zones. Two people may not need equal halves if their
    clothing routines are different. One person may need deeper drawers for workwear, while
    another may need small drawers for activewear or accessories. Assigned drawers often work
    better than one large mixed unit.
  </p>

  <h2>Kids' Rooms, Guest Rooms and Changing Needs</h2>
  <p>
    Kids' rooms benefit from simple categories that can change as clothing sizes change.
    School uniforms, sports gear, sleepwear and everyday T-shirts may need lower or easier
    drawers. Complicated layouts can be harder to reset, especially when laundry is being put
    away quickly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Guest rooms usually need fewer drawers than main bedrooms. A partly empty drawer can be
    more useful than a dresser filled with household overflow. If a spare-room drawer unit is
    full of old cables, spare bedding, paperwork and random items, guests still have nowhere
    practical to unpack.
  </p>
  <p>
    Follow manufacturer instructions for use, weight limits and securing furniture where
    relevant. Avoid treating drawers as steps, avoid overloading top drawers, and keep the
    setup simple enough for the room to adapt over time.
  </p>

  <h2>Materials, Cleaning and Everyday Wear</h2>
  <p>
    Laminate, timber-look, solid timber, metal, painted finishes, fabric drawers and plastic
    drawer units all behave differently. No material is automatically right for every home.
    Dark finishes can show dust, glossy finishes can show fingerprints, and fabric drawers
    can collect dust or sag when overloaded.
  </p>
  <p>
    Timber and veneer can mark from water, oils or heavy items left on top. Metal runners,
    drawer bases and handles should feel suitable for the way the unit will be used. A drawer
    that works for spare linen may not cope as well with heavy daily clothing if it is
    overloaded.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cleaning around and under the furniture matters. Check whether the unit can be moved if
    needed, whether there is enough floor clearance to clean beneath it and whether the
    finish suits the household's everyday habits.
  </p>

  <h2>Stability, Weight Limits and Manufacturer Guidance</h2>
  <p>
    Tall furniture deserves more stability consideration than lower furniture. Check the
    manufacturer's instructions, weight limits and guidance before use. Avoid overloading
    upper drawers, shelves, tops, runners or handles, and keep heavier items lower where
    practical.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some furniture is intended to be secured according to manufacturer guidance. Renters
    should check approval before drilling or making permanent changes. If installation or
    wall fixing is required, use appropriate qualified help where needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not use drawers as steps or leave heavy items balanced on top. No furniture item
    should be treated as a complete solution on its own. The practical goal is to choose,
    place and use the unit according to the guidance supplied with it.
  </p>

  <h2>Trade-Offs Worth Knowing</h2>
  <p>
    Tallboys save floor width but add height and visual bulk. Low dressers provide surface
    space but need more wall width. Deep drawers hold bulky clothing but can hide smaller
    items. Shallow drawers suit small pieces but may not handle jumpers, tracksuits or spare
    linen.
  </p>
  <p>
    More drawers create more categories to maintain. A matching bedroom set may look tidy but
    still be wrong for the actual room. A cheaper drawer unit may be enough for light use,
    while daily clothing may need stronger runners and sturdier drawer bases. Heavy furniture
    can feel substantial but be harder for renters to move later.
  </p>
  <p>
    Extra folded-clothing capacity can be useful, but open floor space is valuable too. If a
    drawer unit makes the room harder to move through, the household may be better served by
    sorting clothing, improving the wardrobe or using seasonal space elsewhere.
  </p>

  <h2>Before You Buy Checklist</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Sort clothing before buying drawers.</li>
    <li>Decide what needs to fold, hang, move or leave.</li>
    <li>Measure wall width.</li>
    <li>Measure furniture depth.</li>
    <li>Measure drawer-opening clearance.</li>
    <li>Check bed, wardrobe, door and walkway access.</li>
    <li>Check power points, vents, windows and skirting boards.</li>
    <li>Decide whether a tallboy, low dresser or chest of drawers suits the room shape.</li>
    <li>Check drawer depth and width against the items you plan to store.</li>
    <li>Check manufacturer weight limits and instructions.</li>
    <li>Avoid overloading drawers, tops, runners or shelves.</li>
    <li>Think about whether the top surface will become cluttered.</li>
    <li>Check whether the unit can be cleaned around.</li>
    <li>Avoid permanent fixing in rentals unless approved.</li>
    <li>Secure furniture according to manufacturer guidance where relevant.</li>
    <li>Do not buy a larger unit just because clothing has not been sorted yet.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying drawers before sorting clothes.</li>
    <li>Measuring only wall width and forgetting drawer-opening space.</li>
    <li>Choosing a tallboy that feels too visually heavy for the room.</li>
    <li>Choosing a low dresser that blocks a walkway.</li>
    <li>Buying deep drawers for small items without dividers.</li>
    <li>Using the top as a permanent laundry pile.</li>
    <li>Blocking wardrobe doors or robe tracks.</li>
    <li>Ignoring carpet, rugs or uneven flooring.</li>
    <li>Overloading drawers.</li>
    <li>Treating a drawer unit as a fix for owning too many clothes.</li>
    <li>Buying matching furniture that does not suit the room.</li>
    <li>Forgetting that renters may not be able to use permanent wall fixings without approval.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Suitability-Based Product Angles</h2>
  <p>
    For small bedrooms, a narrower tallboy may be worth considering if it leaves enough
    walkway and drawer clearance. For renters, freestanding units can be flexible, but
    manufacturer guidance and rental approval still matter where fixing is involved.
  </p>
  <p>
    For shared bedrooms, assigned drawers or separate units may work better than one large
    mixed drawer set. For folded clothes, drawer depth and category planning matter more than
    the number of drawers. For kids' rooms, simple drawers with clear categories may be
    easier to maintain than complicated layouts.
  </p>
  <p>
    For guest rooms, a smaller unit or partly empty dresser may be more useful than filling
    the room with overflow. For wardrobe overflow, improve the wardrobe first, then buy
    drawers only for items that genuinely need them. For spare linen, check whether the
    bedroom is the right place or whether under-bed or linen-cupboard space makes more sense.
  </p>

  <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
  <p>
    Bedroom drawers, tallboys and dressers are useful only when they match the room and the
    clothing plan. The strongest choice starts with sorting what needs to fold, measuring the
    space properly and checking how the drawers will open in daily use.
  </p>
  <p>
    A well-sized unit with clear categories will usually help more than a larger piece of
    furniture bought to hide an unsorted wardrobe problem. Start with the clothes, then the
    room measurements, then the furniture.
  </p>

